James K. Randall (June 16, 1929 - Cleveland, Ohio ; May 28, 2014 - Princeton, New Jersey) was an American composer, music theorist, and early adopter of electronic music.
He joined the faculty of Princeton University in 1957.

He also taught for four years at the US Navy School of Music while on active duty.
At Princeton, he became a pioneer in electronic music, working from the very early days of punch cards.
Music from that time includes Lyric Variations for Violin and Computer, Quartets in Pairs, and Quartersines.
J.K. Randall was married to Ruth Hochheimer Randall for 62 years.
